ssroom spaces and the dynamics that emerged between performers and audiences in the Prison Monologues. Blending ethnography, literary studies, psychological analysis, and criminal justice critique, Trapedo Sims centers the often-overlooked stories of incarcerated Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander women in Hawai‘i in ways that resound with the broader American narrative: the disproportionate incarceration of people of color in the prison-industrial complex.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismy21st centuryzHawaii. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorszHawaii. 0aAmerican literaturezHawaiixWomen authors. 0aAmerican literaturezHawaiiy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPrisoners' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticismzHawaii. 0aPrisoners' writings, AmericanzHawaiixHistory and criticism. 0aWomen prisonerszHawaii. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027362?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027362423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027362/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles